# 1-Bit Half Adder

<catsoop-section>Introduction</catsoop-section>

The 1-bit Half Adder chart demonstrates how a computer performs binary addition using the principles of computational thinking. It visually shows how two binary inputs (A and B) are added to produce a **SUM** and a **CARRY** output.

The operation is based on logic gates, where the **XOR gate** gives the SUM and the **AND gate** gives the CARRY. This simple circuit helps students understand how computers process information in binary form and how mathematical operations are executed at the hardware level.

It also encourages analytical and logical thinking by connecting abstract binary concepts with real-life computational processes.

<catsoop-section>Materials Required</catsoop-section>

- 1-bit Half Adder chart

<catsoop-section>Instructions</catsoop-section>

1. Look at the chart. You will see two numbers — A and B.

2. Each number can be 0 or 1 only.

3. The chart shows how a computer adds these two numbers.

4. The XOR gate gives the SUM (the answer).

5. The AND gate gives the CARRY (the extra number).

6. Use this table to check the result:

$$\begin{array}{|c|c||c|c|}
\hline
\textbf{A} & \textbf{B} & \textbf{SUM} & \textbf{CARRY} \\
\hline
0 & 0 & 0 & 0 \\
\hline
0 & 1 & 1 & 0 \\
\hline
1 & 0 & 1 & 0 \\
\hline
1 & 1 & 0 & 1 \\
\hline
\end{array}$$

7. Follow the path shown in the chart.

8. Try different values of A and B and see what happens.

